I thought that was what I wrote? I called the poem an ode to the mundanity of life. I thought it would be obvious I elevated the mundanity of ilfe to something worthy of an ode. I truly like my (largely) no-frills life, and I find joy in the simple things - the warmth of my dog is one of the best things in the universe. I'm not claiming the mundane is only *seemingly* mundane - on the contrary, it *is* mundane, but that is good enough for me to be happy with it. Trying to transcend mundanity usually ended in grief for me (pursuing a career, stepping out of my comfort zone in climbing - none of it was worth it).

Anyway, this is getting too close to poetry, and as a Polish speaker I feel like I can't express myself well enough about any of it in English.

@Andrzej

There have always been critics in one guise or another who believe that art in all its forms needs to be explained to be "understood."  Allowing the art to stand alone, to speak in its own voice, whether a painting, a poem, music, dance or any other form, will speak to you if you give it a chance. Sometimes a reference might make a work of art richer, but dissecting it often just flattens and drains away the quality that makes it art.

Memorizing a poem will allow you to find meaning that you didn't see before; really looking at a painting carefully engages your sensibilities in ways that words can't communicate. Not all art will have meaning to everyone, but you're more likely to find it if you look for it yourself.

@Andrzej

I do remember our discussion about art.  I am not a religious person either, but I value Fra Angelico as much as I do Van Gogh.  On the wall opposite the foot of our bed is a detail of one of his paintings, and it's the first thing I see every morning.  

Saying that poetry is all about a form is like saying that the painting is all about fresco.

